  "Idea": "We propose a novel framework, CausalLatentAttack, that redefines adversarial perturbation in the latent space through the lens of causal disentanglement and adaptive intervention control. Unlike conventional approaches that treat latent vectors as monolithic representations, our method decomposes the latent space into two orthogonal subspaces: (1) a \u2018causal\u2019 subspace encoding semantic features invariant across model architectures (e.g., object shape, pose), and (2) a \u2018non-causal\u2019 subspace capturing superficial, model-specific artifacts (e.g., texture biases, normalization effects). This decomposition is achieved via a causality-regularized VAE trained with inter-model consistency constraints and counterfactual reconstruction objectives. Once disentangled, we introduce a meta-controller—a hierarchical reinforcement learning agent—that learns to apply perturbations selectively within the causal subspace while minimizing changes in the non-causal dimensions. The meta-controller observes real-time feedback including cross-model prediction divergence (as a proxy for transferability), anomaly scores from diverse detectors, and estimated perceptual impact via LPIPS in reconstructed space. Crucially, instead of merely adjusting loss weights, it performs \u2018soft interventions\u2019—modulating the magnitude and direction of perturbations along causal pathways using differentiable backpropagation through the controller-policy network. The policy is trained across a distribution of surrogate models and datasets using PPO, with rewards shaped to maximize attack success on unseen targets under strict stealth budgets. A unique aspect is the integration of \u2018counterfactual guidance\u2019: during training, the system generates counterfactual examples (e.g., \u2018what if this car had no wheels?\u2019) to identify which latent directions are truly predictive versus spurious, reinforcing the controller\u2019s ability to distinguish transferable from detectable changes. This enables dynamic, intention-aware attacks where users specify desired behavior (e.g., \u2018maximize transfer with moderate stealth\u2019), and the controller navigates the causal manifold accordingly. By anchoring perturbations in semantically meaningful, architecture-invariant features, our method achieves superior transferability without increasing detectability—effectively breaking the traditional trade-off. This work bridges adversarial machine learning with causal representation learning, offering profound implications for robustness evaluation, defense design, and understanding the semantic geometry of deep networks.",
  "Title": "CausalLatentAttack: Causal Disentanglement and Intervention Control for Adaptive Adversarial Perturbations in Latent Space",
